05773nam a22007575i 9780231512503DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20082008nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2007049294  a(OCoLC)1013966363  a97802315125037 a10.7312/yu--143262doi  a(DE-B1597)459455  a(OCoLC)979586125  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aPN510b.Y82 2009 4aPN81 7aLIT0080002bisacsh04a809.933821 aYu, Anthony, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aComparative Journeys :bEssays on Literature and Religion East and West /cAnthony Yu. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2008] 4c©2008  a1 online resource (432 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aMasters of Chinese Studies00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- t1. Literature and Religion -- t2. New Gods and Old Order -- t3. Life in the Garden -- t4. The Order of Temptations in Paradise Regained -- t5. Problems and Prospects in Chinese-Western Literary Relations -- t6. Narrative Structure and the Problem of Chapter Nine in the Xiyouji -- t7. Two Literary Examples of Religious Pilgrimage -- t8. Religion and Literature in China -- t9. The Real Tripitaka Revisited -- t10. “Rest, Rest, Perturbed Spirit!” -- t11. Cratylus and the Xunzi on Names -- t12. Reading the Daodejing: Ethics and Politics of the Rhetoric -- t13. Altered Accents: A Comparative View of Liberal Education -- t14. Readability: Religion and the Reception of Translation -- t15. Enduring Change: Confucianism and the Prospect of Human Rights -- t16. China and the Problem of Human Rights: Ancient Verities and Modern Realities -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThroughout his academic career, Anthony C. Yu has employed a comparative approach to literary analysis that pays careful attention to the religious and philosophical elements of Chinese and Western texts. His mastery of both canons remains unmatched in the field, and his immense knowledge of the contexts that gave rise to each tradition supplies the foundations for ideal comparative scholarship. In these essays, Yu explores the overlap between literature and religion in Chinese and Western literature. He opens with a principal method for relating texts to religion and follows with several essays that apply this approach to single texts in discrete traditions: the Greek religion in Prometheus; Christian theology in Milton; ancient Chinese philosophical thought in Laozi; and Chinese religious syncretism in The Journey to the West. Yu's essays juxtapose Chinese and Western textsCratylus next to Xunzi, for exampleand discuss their relationship to language and subjects, such as liberal Greek education against general education in China. He compares a specific Western text and religion to a specific Chinese text and religion. He considers the Divina Commedia in the context of Catholic theology alongside The Journey to the West as it relates to Chinese syncretism, united by the theme of pilgrimage. Yet Yu's focus isn't entirely tied to the classics. He also considers the struggle for human rights in China and how this topic relates to ancient Chinese social thought and modern notions of rights in the West. "In virtually every high-cultural system," Yu writes, "be it the Indic, the Islamic, the Sino-Japanese, or the JudeoChristian, the literary tradition has developed in intimateindeed, often intertwining-relation to religious thought, practice, institution, and symbolism." Comparative Journeys is a major step toward unraveling this complexity, revealing through the skilled observation of texts the extraordinary intimacy between two supposedly disparate languages and cultures.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewe